# Ref Pattern for Callbacks and Effects

**When to apply:** Use when a callback or effect depends on values that change often (e.g. `pending`, `queue`, `opponentState`). The ref pattern keeps the callback stable while still reading the latest value at call time.

**Core rule:** Update refs during render; read them when the handler runs.

**Why:** Closures capture values at creation time. Refs let callbacks read the latest value at call time without recreating the callback.

**Pattern:**
```ts
const pendingRef = useRef(pending)
pendingRef.current = pending  // every render

const handlePlay = useCallback(() => {
  if (pendingRef.current) return
  // ...
}, [])
```

**Safe when:** (1) Update ref every render, (2) Read only in event/callback, (3) Never use for rendering.

**Unsafe when:** Forget to update, use in render, or read in a stale context.

**Example:** [frontend/src/App.tsx](frontend/src/App.tsx): `pendingRef`, `handlePlayRef`, `queueRef`, `gameStartedRef` for keyboard handler and voice batch with `[]` deps.
